  <title>Inverse Variation</title>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Overview</title>
<p>This Lesson continues the study of variation, this time addressing inverse variation.</p></commentary>

<activity><title>Inverse Variation</title>

<task><p>Complete the statements about inverse variation.</p>
  <p><ul>  
  <li><p>The formula for inverse variation is <fillin/> .</p></li>                          
  <li><p>An inverse variation is an example of a  <fillin/> function.</p></li>
  <li><p>The graph of an inverse variation has a  <fillin/> at <m>x=0</m> .</p></li>
  <li><p>If <m>y</m> varies inversely with <m>x</m>, so that <m>y=\dfrac{k}{x}</m>, what is true about the product of the variables?</p></li></ul></p></task>
</activity>

<activity><title>Wrapping Paper</title>

<introduction><p>The marketing department for a paper company is testing wrapping paper rolls in various dimensions to see which shape consumers prefer. All the rolls contain the same amount of wrapping paper.</p>
