                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Width (feet)</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                    <cell>2.5</cell>
                    <cell>3</cell></row>
                <row><cell>Length (feet)</cell>
                    <cell>12</cell>
                    <cell>9.6</cell>
                    <cell>8</cell></row>
                <row><cell>Length <m>\cdot</m> Feet</cell>
                    <cell><m>\hphantom{0000000}</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\hphantom{0000000}</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\hphantom{0000000}</m></cell></row>
    </tabular></introduction>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Point out that not every decreasing function represents inverse variation; we must test for <m>xy=k</m>.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Compute the product of the length and width for each roll of wrapping paper. What is the constant of inverse proportionality?</p></task>

<task><p>Express the length, <m>L</m> of the paper as a function of the width, <m>w</m> of the roll.</p></task> 

<task><p>Sketch a graph of the function. Which basic graph does your answer resemble?</p>
      <image source="act-5-5-1.png" width="35%"></image></task>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Note that in direct variation, the graph passes through the origin, but in inverse variation the function is undefined at <m>x=0</m>. The graph has both a vertical and a horizontal asymptote.</p></commentary>
</activity>

